<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-907-840  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 907 840.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 28 1989 v3 n35 p1(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>National Guard feels congressional ADP pinch. (Automated DataProcessing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brewin, Bob; Poos, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The National Guard has been forced to slow down its automationplans because of legislation which forbids it to acquire newhardware until the $1 billion Reserve Component Automation Systemm (RACS) is ready in 1992.andP;  The legislation is intended to haltspending on computer systems until an overall plan is in effect tostandardize computer equipment.andP;  As of Jul 31, 1989, 1,960specially upgraded Unisys B-26 microcomputers had been deliveredas part of the Tactical Army Combat Service Support ComputerSystem (TACCS) to be used as mobile field offices.andP;  However, thesecomputers are only designated for use in training applications,not the data automation and peacetime uses for which the RACSequipment is intended.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Unisys Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    UIS.andO;Product:   Unisys B26 (Microcomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     United States. National GuardData ProcessingAutomationApplicationsBureaucracy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>